The syntax coloring looks great!  I recall that when I was looking at it before, there was a way to add to the keyword list, but I don't remember the details, sorry.

The kbd css should have a mini border around it.  It's meant for showing keycaps, not keyboard input.

This is wikipedia's style, which I personally find appealing:
<pre>
kbd { border: 1px solid #aaa; -moz-border-radius: 0.2em; -webkit-border-radius: 0.2em; border-radius: 0.2em; -moz-box-shadow: 0.1em 0.1em 0.2em rgba(0,0,0,0.1); -webkit-box-shadow: 0.1em 0.1em 0.2em rgba(0,0,0,0.1); box-shadow: 0.1em 0.1em 0.2em rgba(0,0,0,0.1); background-color: #f9f9f9; background-image: -moz-linear-gradient(top, #eee, #f9f9f9, #eee); background-image: -o-linear-gradient(top, #eee, #f9f9f9, #eee); background-image: -webkit-linear-gradient(top, #eee, #f9f9f9, #eee); background-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, #eee, #f9f9f9, #eee); padding: 0.1em 0.3em; font-family: inherit; font-size: 0.85em; }
</pre>
Lots of examples on this page: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keyboard_layout

I think this is stackoverflow's style, which is a decent alternative:
<pre>
kbd {
    display: inline-block;
    margin: 0 .1em;
    padding: .1em .6em;
    font-family: Arial,"Helvetica Neue",Helvetica,sans-serif;
    font-size: 11px;
    line-height: 1.4;
    color: #242729;
    text-shadow: 0 1px 0 #FFF;
    background-color: #e1e3e5;
    border: 1px solid #adb3b9;
    border-radius: 3px;
    box-shadow: 0 1px 0 rgba(12,13,14,0.2), 0 0 0 2px #FFF inset;
    white-space: nowrap;
}</pre>
Some examples here: https://meta.stackoverflow.com/questions/270967/proper-use-of-the-kbd-tag

Cheers!

I've been experimenting with the rnd(n) function.

for n of 1 through 32767, it seems to return random values in the range of [0..n)
for n of 0, it seems to return random values between [-1..0]
for n of -32767 through -1, it seems to return random (-32768..32768)
for n of -32768, it seems to return (0..32768)
